## Q9 — Musnad al-Rabīʿ b. Ḥabīb: the anti-anthropomorphism corpus

### Structural framing (confirmed)

The standard recension is *al-Jāmiʿ al-Ṣaḥīḥ — Musnad al-Imām al-Rabīʿ b. Ḥabīb*, arranged by Abū Yaʿqūb Yūsuf b. Ibrāhīm al-Wārijlānī (d. 570/1174). It contains roughly **1,005 reports** in four parts: Parts I–II (~742 marfūʿ muttaṣil via al-Rabīʿ ← Abū ʿUbayda Muslim b. Abī Karīma ← Jābir b. Zayd ← Companion ← Prophet); **Part III**, titled *Āthār iḥtajja bihā al-Rabīʿ ʿalā mukhālifīhi* (~140 athār — the polemical-creedal section, including the tawḥīd cluster); Part IV (~123 reports of Maḥbūb b. al-Ruḥayl ← al-Rabīʿ, Aflaḥ b. ʿAbd al-Wahhāb ← Abū Ghānim al-Khurāsānī, plus marāsīl Jābir). Editions of reference: Dār al-Ḥikma / Maktabat al-Istiqāma (Beirut, 1415/1995, ed. Muḥammad Idrīs and ʿĀshūr b. Yūsuf); critical edition Mansouri/Drissi/Mizouri (Oman, 2018); Sharḥ al-Sālimī in 3 volumes (Muscat, 1993). **Confidence: VH.**

### (a) Tawḥīd section — chapter list and contents

**Evidence (VH for chapter titles, retrieved from ketabonline.com TOC of the Dār al-Ḥikma edn., and usul.ai for Part-I verbatim).** The tawḥīd cluster sits in Part III. Verified bab titles include: bab 158 *on what is narrated from ʿAlī b. Abī Ṭālib on exalting Allāh and negating likeness (tashbīh) to Him*; bab 162 *Ibn ʿAbbās on tanzīh*; bab 163 *the story of Nāfiʿ b. al-Azraq with Ibn ʿAbbās*; bab 164 *on his (the Prophet's) saying: "Khalaqa Llāhu Ādama ʿalā ṣūratihi"*; bab 165 *ʿUmar and Ibn Masʿūd on tanzīh al-Bārī*; bab 166 *Ibn ʿAbbās on Q 75:22–23 "wujūhun yawmaʾidhin nāḍira ilā rabbihā nāẓira"*; bab 167 *Ibn ʿAbbās again on al-naẓar*.

A retrieved fragment from bab 164 (vol. 1, p. 318 of the Dār al-Ḥikma edn.) preserves Ibn ʿAbbās's polemical dialogue with the Azraqite Nāfiʿ:

> **«... وهو بكل أينٍ — يعني: بكل مكان. قال: فسكت ابنُ الأزرق. قال ابن عباس: لا تمضي الليالي والأيام حتى يتفقَّه قومٌ في الشرائع وهم عن توحيد الله غافلون، قومٌ يصفون ربَّهم بالبشر ...»**
> *"'…and He is in every "where" — meaning in every place.' Ibn al-Azraq fell silent. Ibn ʿAbbās said: 'The nights and days shall not pass until a people become learned in the legal sciences while heedless of the tawḥīd of Allāh — a people who describe their Lord in terms of a human being (bashar)…'"*

The hermeneutical maneuver is decisive: the title of bab 164 quotes the contested Sunni hadith *"khalaqa Llāhu Ādama ʿalā ṣūratihi"*, but the *content* refers the pronoun back to Adam (not God) and pre-empts the anthropomorphic reading using Ibn ʿAbbās material.

Already in Part I, bab 4 (*al-ʿilm wa-ṭalabuhu*), ḥadīth #28, the Musnad embeds a programmatic anti-anthropomorphism Prophetic statement (verbatim retrieved from usul.ai):

> **«... ثم قام إلى الثالثة فوجدهم يذكرون توحيد الله عز وجل ونفي الأشباه والأمثال عنه، فجلس إليهم كثيراً، ثم قال: "بهذا أمرني ربي". قال جابر: لأن التوحيد معرفة الله عز وجل ومن لا يعرف توحيد الله فليس بمؤمن.»**
> *"…Then he came to the third [circle] and found them mentioning the tawḥīd of Allāh and negating from Him resemblances and likenesses (nafy al-ashbāh wa-l-amthāl) — he sat with them at length, then said: 'With this my Lord has commanded me.' Jābir said: 'Because tawḥīd is the (true) knowledge of Allāh, and whoever does not know the tawḥīd of Allāh is not a believer.'"*

**Analysis.** The Musnad does not contain a self-standing *Kitāb al-Tawḥīd* parallel to Bukhārī's book 97. Tawḥīd material is bilayered: (i) scattered foundational reports in Part I (e.g. ḥ. 28; ḥ. 61 with ʿĀʾisha denying that Muḥammad saw his Lord, *man zaʿama anna Muḥammadan raʾā rabbahu fa-qad aʿẓama ʿalā Allāh al-firya*); (ii) the systematic anti-anthropomorphism cluster in babs 158–167+ of Part III, built almost entirely from athār of ʿAlī, ʿUmar, Ibn Masʿūd, and especially Ibn ʿAbbās — and notably anchoring Ibadi tanzīh in Ibn ʿAbbās's polemic against the *Azāriqa* Khārijites (a different deviant sect), which doubles as Ibadi self-differentiation. **Confidence: VH** for chapter structure and ḥ. 28; **H** for content of babs 162–167 (verbatim of every individual hadith therein not retrieved).

**Null per source.** Verbatim Arabic of all individual hadith in babs 158–185 was not retrieved; shamela.ws did not yield direct page-level access; sunnah.com does not host the Musnad.

### (b) Sifat hadith in the Musnad but not in Bukhārī/Muslim

The clearest unique-to-Ibadi tawḥīd text is **ḥ. 28** quoted above: the explicit Prophetic endorsement of *nafy al-ashbāh wa-l-amthāl* as the divinely-commanded core of the religion. No equivalent matn exists in the Ṣaḥīḥayn; the closest Sunni parallels report knowledge-circles but lack the anti-anthropomorphism clause. The **bab-164 Ibn ʿAbbās/Ibn al-Azraq dialogue** including *"qawmun yaṣifūna rabbahum bi-l-bashar"* ("a people who describe their Lord in terms of a human being") is likewise absent from Bukhārī and Muslim in this form. **Babs 162, 165, 166, 167** consist of Companion *athār* on tanzīh — a category structurally underrepresented in the Ṣaḥīḥayn's tawḥīd books, which are dominated by *marfūʿ* Prophetic affirmations of divine attributes. **Confidence: H** (verbatim of every athar not retrieved; structural-arrangement evidence robust).

### (c) Sifat hadith in Bukhārī/Muslim but absent from the Musnad

Based on the complete retrieved chapter index, the Musnad contains **no bab** corresponding to any of the major Sunni *ṣifāt khabariyya* hadith:

| Sunni hadith | Bukhārī/Muslim citation | Present in al-Rabīʿ |
|---|---|---|
| Ḥadīth al-nuzūl (God descends to the lowest heaven) | Bukh. 1145; Muslim 758 | **Absent.** The Musnad encourages duʿāʾ in the last third of the night without the descent clause. |
| Ḥadīth al-ruʾya (believers see God like the full moon) | Bukh. 554, 4851, 7434–36; Muslim 633 | **Absent in marfūʿ form.** Replaced by Ibn ʿAbbās tafsīr of Q 75:23 (babs 166–167) and ʿĀʾisha's denial in ḥ. 61. |
| Ḥadīth al-sāq (God uncovers His shin) | Bukh. 4919; Muslim 183 | **Absent.** |
| Ḥadīth al-qadam (God's foot in Jahannam) | Bukh. 4848, 7384; Muslim 2848 | **Absent.** |
| Ḥadīth al-ḍaḥik (God laughs) | Bukh. 2826; Muslim 1890 | **Absent.** |
| *Khalaqa Llāhu Ādama ʿalā ṣūratihi* read anthropomorphically | Bukh. 6227; Muslim 2841 | **Wording present** (bab 164 title) **but reinterpreted via Ibn ʿAbbās athār** to refer the pronoun to Adam. |

**Confidence: H** — this is strong negative evidence based on the complete chapter index, but not exhaustive verbatim verification.

### (d) Analysis of divergence as institutional/sectarian selection

The pattern is coherent and editorially purposive. (1) **Positive inclusion**: programmatic Prophetic endorsement of *nafy al-ashbāh wa-l-amthāl* placed early (ḥ. 28); Companion-athār cluster of tanzīh anchored to non-anthropomorphist authorities (ʿAlī, ʿUmar, Ibn Masʿūd, Ibn ʿAbbās). (2) **Negative exclusion**: no chapter, anywhere, collects the ṣifāt khabariyya hadith that fill Bukhārī's *Kitāb al-Tawḥīd*. (3) **Hermeneutic pre-emption**: where a contested matn is included (*ṣūratihi*), surrounding athār immediately neutralize the anthropomorphic reading. (4) **The Q 75:23 problem**: Sunni tradition reads this verse + Jarīr's ruʾya hadith as proof of beatific vision; the Musnad treats Q 75:23 via Ibn ʿAbbās's *tafsīr* (intizār, "awaiting reward") only, with no Prophetic ruʾya proof. **The Musnad is the hadith engine of Ibadi kalām**, supplying textual cover for what al-Sālimī's *Mashāriq Anwār al-ʿUqūl* and al-Janāwunī's *Waḍʿ* later elaborate as *tanzīh muṭlaq*.

**Cross-reference to project theme.** Three flags. *(i)* Three independent early streams — Ibadi, Imāmī (al-Kāfī's *Kitāb al-Tawḥīd*), and Muʿtazilī — converge on a transcendent picture, while the anthropomorphic corpus is largely confined to the proto-Sunnī/Ahl al-Ḥadīth stream. *(ii)* The Ibadi short isnād (Basran 1st–2nd c. AH) preserves a radically transcendent picture, consistent with — but not proving — the hypothesis that anthropomorphic strata accreted later. *(iii)* **Critical caveat**: Sunni polemicists (Albānī, Mashhūr Ḥasan) argue the Musnad's surviving form is a 6th/12th-c. al-Wārijlānī compilation; if so, Ibadi "absence" reflects medieval Ibadi kalām filtration, not 2nd-c. purity. The directional editorial pressure is documentable; its terminus a quo is not. **Confidence: H** descriptive; **L** for strongest hypothesis form.

