## Q10 — Jābir ibn Zayd: surviving fragments and the Naffāth burning

### (a) The Diwan and its destruction

**Evidence.** The Ibadi tradition unanimously reports that Jābir composed a vast compendium — *Dīwān Jābir* / *al-Mudawwana al-Kubrā* — variously described as "seven loads" (سبعة أحمال) or "ten camel-loads" of material covering tafsīr, hadith, ʿaqīda, and fiqh. **The Diwan did not survive**. Two destruction narratives compete:

1. **The Mongol/Fatimid theory** (favored in modern popular Omani accounts): Basran copy lost in the 1258 sack of Baghdad; Maghribi copy lost under the Fatimids.

2. **The Naffāth burning** (the internal Ibadi narrative, transmitted through al-Wisyānī's *Siyar* citing Yakhlaftan b. Ayyūb al-Nafūsī, then repeated in al-Darjīnī's *Ṭabaqāt al-Mashāyikh* and al-Shammākhī's *Kitāb al-Siyar*). The custody chain: Jābir → Abū ʿUbayda Muslim b. Abī Karīma (d. ~145 AH) → Abū Sufyān Maḥbūb b. al-Ruḥayl → his son ʿAbd Allāh b. Maḥbūb, *"and it was taken from them at Mecca"* (وأُخذ عنهم بمكة). Subsequently the copy passed to **Naffāth b. Naṣr al-Nafūsī**, a North African Ibadi dissident opposed to the Rustamid imamate of Tāhart (late 2nd / early 3rd c. AH), who **destroyed it** (أتلفها).

**Crucial identification.** The perpetrator is **not al-Ḥajjāj b. Yūsuf**. Al-Ḥajjāj imprisoned and exiled Jābir but did not burn the Diwan. The destroyer was an *insider* — a doctrinal opponent of the Rustamid mainstream from within the Ibadi network itself.

**Analysis.** The Naffāth narrative is preserved exclusively through internal Ibadi tabaqāt; the loss is attributed to factional politics among Ibadis. This is theologically and historically loaded: the perpetrator knew the contents intimately and considered them a political/doctrinal threat. The "Mongol/Fatimid loss" narrative is later, simpler, and may be apologetic camouflage.

**Confidence: H** for Naffāth attribution; **M** for retrievable exact-page citations in al-Shammākhī (the Maṭbaʿa al-Bārūniyya 1301/1883 edition exists on archive.org as unpaginated OCR).

**Null.** No verbatim Arabic of the Naffāth episode retrieved from al-Darjīnī or al-Shammākhī at exact-page resolution; the Wisyānī chain quotation above is the closest. No fragment of the Diwan *as such* is securely identified; the "Kitāb al-Ṣalāt" and "Kitāb al-Nikāḥ" MSS at the Bārūniyya library, Jerba, are speculated by ʿAmr al-Nāmī to be Diwan-fragments but this is conjectural.

**Cross-reference.** Directly bears on the project's "suppression = signal" hypothesis: an insider burning by a doctrinal opponent suggests the destroyed content was considered dangerous *to the dominant Ibadi reading*, not to outsiders.

### (b) Surviving letters

**Confirmed and published**: **Rasāʾil al-Imām Jābir b. Zayd al-Azdī (t. 93 AH)**, *ḍabṭ naṣṣihā*: Dr. ʿAmr b. Khalīfa al-Nāmī; review/preparation: Sulṭān b. Mubārak al-Shaybānī; Dār al-Daʿwa, Nālūt (Libya) / Mīzāb (Algeria), 1st ed. 1439/2018. Manuscript base: al-Bārūniyya library, al-Ḥishshān, Jerba, Tunisia (discovered by al-Nāmī, Jumādā al-Ūlā 1388 / Aug 1968), 232 pp., ~14 lines/page, Maghribi script likely 6th c. AH, first folio missing. Contains **17 letters** to named followers including Rāshid b. Khaytham, ʿUthmān b. Yasār, al-Ḥārith b. ʿAmr, Sālim b. Dhakwān, ʿAbd al-Malik b. al-Muhallab, Khabra bint Ḍamra. Formula: «من جابر بن زيد إلى ... سلام عليكم، فإني أحمد إليك الله ...».

Two passages directly reveal the underground security protocols of the early Ibadi network. To ʿAbd al-Malik b. al-Muhallab: «اكتب إليّ بما كانت لك من حاجة في سر وثقة، فإنك قد علمت الذي نحن فيه وما نتخوف من الذي يطلب العلل علينا» — *"Write to me about whatever needs you have in secret and trust, for you know what we are in and what we fear from those who seek pretexts against us."* To al-Ḥārith b. ʿAmr: «واعلم أنك أصلحك الله بأرض أكره أن تذكر لي فيها اسما، فلا ترو شيئا مما كتبت إليك» — *"You are in a land in which I dislike to mention any name to you, so do not transmit anything I write to you."*

A separate edition, ***Min Jawābāt al-Imām Jābir b. Zayd***, arranged by Shaykh Saʿīd b. Khalaf al-Khurūṣī (Oman), combines two riwāya-collections: Abū Ṣafra ʿAbd al-Malik b. Ṣafra ← al-Rabīʿ ← Ḍimām b. al-Sāʾib ← Jābir; and Ḥabīb b. Abī Ḥabīb ṣāḥib al-anmāṭ ← ʿAmr b. Haram ← Jābir. A famous **letter of Jābir to al-Zuhrī** rebuking him for joining the Umayyad court is cited by al-Wārijlānī in *al-Dalīl wa-l-Burhān* (verbatim not retrieved). A separate "Risāla to a Shīʿī man" listed in al-Barrādī's catalog **did not survive**.

**Confidence: VH** on the Rasāʾil edition; **H** on the Jawābāt and Zuhrī letter.

### (c) Jābir in the later Ibadi encyclopedias

**Confirmed.** *Bayān al-Sharʿ* of Muḥammad b. Ibrāhīm al-Kindī (d. 508/1115), Muscat: Wizārat al-Turāth al-Qawmī wa-l-Thaqāfa, 1st printing 1404/1984, 30 (or in some catalogues 72) vols., *taḥqīq*: committee under Aḥmad b. Ḥamad al-Khalīlī, citing Jābir extensively (per Fahd al-Saʿdī's bibliographic study *al-Maṣādir Ghayr al-ʿUmāniyya fī Kitāb Bayān al-Sharʿ*); the *Muṣannaf* of Aḥmad b. ʿAbd Allāh al-Kindī (d. 557/1162), 41 vols.; the *Jāmiʿ Ibn Jaʿfar* of Abū Jābir Muḥammad b. Jaʿfar al-Izkawī (3rd c. AH), the earliest surviving Omani Ibadi fiqh compendium.

A concrete preserved Jābir-opinion accessible cross-confessionally appears in *Muṣannaf ʿAbd al-Razzāq* #13591 (a Sunni source): «عن سفيان، عن عبَّاد، عن منصور، عن جابر بن زيد أبي الشعثاء قال: "هو ماؤك فأهرقه"» — Jābir's permissive ruling on istimnāʾ ("It is your water, so spill it"). Many other Jābir rulings (slaughter posture, hajj, inheritance, prayer) survive scattered through ʿAbd al-Razzāq, Ibn Abī Shayba, and Saʿīd b. Manṣūr; these are gathered in Khalfān al-Ṭīwānī's *Fatāwā al-Imām Jābir b. Zayd*. **Jābir's chronological ordering of Qurʾanic sūras** is preserved (e.g. Sūrat al-Aʿrāf as 39th, cited by Ibn ʿĀshūr in *al-Taḥrīr wa-l-Tanwīr*).

**Confidence: M** for the encyclopedias themselves; **H** for transmission chains; **L** for retrieving discrete verbatim Jābir quotations *by exact volume/page* in Bayān al-Sharʿ or Muṣannaf al-Kindī in open digital sources.

### (d) Creation, cosmology, soul, jinn — the conspicuous null

**This is a strong null with project-thematic significance.** The 17 *Rasāʾil* and the *Jawābāt* are overwhelmingly fiqhī and akhlāqī. The complete chapter list of the Jawābāt covers ṭahāra; ḥayḍ; ṣalāt; janāʾiz; zakāt; ṣiyām; ḥajj; nadhr/aymān; dhakāt/aḍāḥī; nikāḥ; ṭalāq; waṣāyā; mamālīk/ʿitq; buyūʿ; mīrāth; firāsh/āniya/libās; ʿilm wa-ādāb; aḥkām wa-shahādāt. **There is no chapter on khalq, rūḥ, jinn, or cosmology.** No surviving Jābir tafsīr-fragment addresses the jinn-creation verses (Q 15:27, Q 55:15) or the nafkha verses (Q 15:29, Q 38:72, Q 32:9). A minor exception: Jābir transmits the chronological positioning of Sūrat al-Jinn after al-Aʿrāf, but this is meta-textual, not substantive.

**Analysis.** Given (i) Jābir's direct discipleship under Ibn ʿAbbās (the great early authority on cosmology and demonology), (ii) the Ibadi tabaqāt's report that the lost Diwan contained "*ārāʾahu fī umūr al-ʿaqīda*", and (iii) the destroyer (Naffāth) being a doctrinal opponent, this absence is *structurally suggestive*: the destroyed material is precisely the cosmological/doctrinal corpus that does not appear in what survived. The surviving stream — the fiqh transmission through Abū ʿUbayda and al-Rabīʿ — was preserved because it was operationally needed by the underground community; the doctrinal/cosmological material was either factionally contested or transmitted orally and lost.

**Confidence: H** for the null on the Rasāʾil/Jawābāt tables of contents; **M** for the broader claim across Bayān al-Sharʿ etc. (not exhaustively searched).

**Cross-reference flags.** The *Naffāth* event is the cleanest case-study for the "suppression = signal" frame: an insider with custody of the Diwan destroyed it for doctrinal reasons. Jābir's reported meta-statement «إنا لله، يكتبون عني آراء وقد أرجع عنها غدا» ("they write down opinions from me which I may retract tomorrow") is itself a flag of doctrinal mutability in the early period. The Sunni biographical tradition (Bukhārī, Ibn Saʿd, Dhahabī) records a deathbed disavowal of the Ibadis attributed to Jābir — contested by Ibadis as forgery — but this is a parallel narrative-conflict worth noting.

