### (b) Sūrat al-Jinn (Q 72)

Aṭfayyish's *Taysīr* on Q 72:1 reproduces the standard report-tradition (the jinn of Naṣībīn at Baṭn Nakhla, between Mecca and Ṭāʾif, while the Prophet recited al-Fajr) — narratively conservative. But on Q 72:3 (*taʿālā jaddu rabbinā*) he glosses: «**تنزه جلاله وعظمته عما نُسب إليه**» — *"His majesty and greatness are transcendent above what has been attributed to Him."* This is exegetically strategic: the jinn's own confession is used as Qurʾanic proof of divine *tanzīh* — the jinn, upon hearing the Qurʾan, immediately abandon anthropomorphism (*ṣāḥiba wa-walad*). On Q 72:6 Aṭfayyish polemically extends this against contemporary saint-veneration practices.

