## Q13 — Pre-Islamic Oman: Magan, Zoroastrianism, the arrival of Islam

### Scope note

Pre-Islamic Oman has no native epigraphy comparable to South Arabia's Sabaic/Minaic corpus. Reconstruction relies on Mesopotamian cuneiform references to Magan, mute archaeological material, brief Achaemenid/Sasanian inscriptions, and much later Arabic Muslim historiographies that retroject genealogy and politics. Confidence is weighted accordingly.

### (a) General pre-Islamic religious practices

There is no specific textual evidence in classical Arab sources that the five Noachic idols of Q 71:23 (Wadd, Suwāʿ, Yaghūth, Yaʿūq, Nasr) had cult centers in Oman proper. The Azd genealogy in al-Awtabī's *Kitāb al-Ansāb* (11th c., ed. D. Amaldi, *Arabia Antica* 13) traces Omani Arab tribes back to migration from Maʾrib but supplies essentially no detailed pre-Islamic theology. Iron-Age archaeology (A. Benoist, *Arabian Archaeology and Epigraphy* 18 [2007]: 34–54; in Avanzini ed., *Eastern Arabia during the First Millennium BC*, 2010, pp. 109–142) documents columned cultic halls at Rumeilah, Bithnah, Muweilah, Salut, but no inscriptions naming deities. **Confidence: M** on indigenous serpent cult; **L** on naming any South Arabian deity in Oman. **Null**: no epigraphic deity-name anywhere on any Bronze/Iron-Age site in Oman.

### (b) Magan-period cultic evidence

**Bat / al-Khutm / al-Ayn** (UNESCO World Heritage 434, inscribed 1988): two major Bronze-Age tomb traditions — Hafit beehive tombs (c. 3200–2700 BCE) and Umm an-Nar multi-chambered tombs (c. 2700–2000 BCE, up to ~200 interments). The seven stone "towers" (~20–25 m diameter) are of disputed function. No inscriptions; cultic interpretation rests on architectural elaboration, secondary processing of remains, and grave goods (Indus carnelian, Mesopotamian pottery).

**Hili (UAE side)**: Cleuziou & Vogt, "Umm an-Nar Burial Customs," *PSAS* 13 (1983): 37–52; bull and snake reliefs on tomb facade stones (Hili, Mowaihat). **Dahwa 7** Umm an-Nar settlement: Y. Douglas et al., "A ritual building from the Umm an-Nar settlement, Dahwa 7," *AAE* 2024 — the first formally identified small ritual structures in an Umm an-Nar settlement context, separate from tombs.

**Bisya/Salut** (Italian Mission to Oman, dir. A. Avanzini, then A. Zanini): Avanzini ed., *In the Heart of Oman: The Castle of Salut* (L'Erma di Bretschneider, 2015); Condoluci et al., "High Places in Oman" (Academia.edu). The Iron Age II cultic site on Jebel al-Aqma near Bisya yielded copper snake figurines, ceramic vessels with snake appliqué, votive arrowheads/daggers, columned hall architecture. **Mudhmar East near Adam**: French Mission (G. Gernez et al.), "New Evidence of Iron Age Ritual Practices in Central Oman" (*PSAS*), Buildings 1 and 2 with abundant snake figurines, miniature votive weapons, anthropomorphic figurines.

**The snake/serpent cult (Iron Age II, c. 1000–600 BCE)** is the clearest peer-reviewed Omani cultic phenomenon: A. Benoist, "An Iron Age II Snake Cult in the Oman Peninsula: Evidence from Bithnah," *AAE* 18/1 (2007): 34–54; Benoist 2010, "Snake, copper and water in south-eastern Arabian religion during the Iron Age" — proposing association of snakes with copper metallurgy and water/falaj. Connected sites: Bithnah, Masāfī, al-Qusais, Saruq al-Hadid (Dubai, >200 kg ferrous remains plus extensive snake iconography), ʿUqdat al-Bakrah, Jebel Muḍmar, Husn Salut, Mudhmar East. **Ras al-Jinz / Ras al-Hadd** (Joint Hadd Project, Cleuziou & Tosi, 1985–2011): RJ-2 (Umm an-Nar, c. 2500–2000 BCE) — richest seal assemblage in Oman, Indus pottery (~20% of ceramics), bitumen with reed/rope/plank impressions (boat caulking).

**Falaj-ritual link**: Costa & Wilkinson, *The Hinterland of Sohar* (1987) — of 23 surveyed systems, only one with pre-Islamic evidence, none Sasanian-dated; the "Persian falaj origin" claim is undermined.

**Analysis.** Magan/Umm an-Nar religion is mostly funerary and symbolic; afterlife belief is inferable from elaborate communal tombs, secondary processing of remains, and grave goods. The clearest well-published Iron Age cultic phenomenon is the SE Arabian snake cult, tied to water and metal, attested at multiple independent sites across UAE and central Oman, strongly suggesting a regionally autochthonous serpent veneration. **No deity is identifiable by name.** **Confidence: H** for snake-cult horizon; **H** for tower-tomb funerary culture; **M** for ritual interpretation of building functions; **L** for deity identification (none possible).

### (c) Achaemenid, Sasanian, Zoroastrian presence

**Achaemenid (Maka satrapy).** Behistun inscription (c. 520 BCE) lists Maka as a satrapy; Akkadian equivalent Qadē; Assurbanipal's Ištar Slab cites tribute from Padē king of Qadē, capital at Iz/skie (= Izki, interior Oman). Persepolis Fortification Tablets PF 679–680 (per Potts, *A Companion to the Achaemenid Persian Empire*, Wiley 2021) record satraps at Makkaš c. 505/4 BCE: Irdumašda (*R̥tāmazdā*) and Zamašba (*Jāmāspa*) — both with Iranian/Zoroastrian theophoric names. Mykians served in Xerxes' army at Thermopylae (Herodotus 7.68). **No Achaemenid material culture excavated in Oman** (Potts, Kennet).

**Sasanian (Mazūn province).** Šābuhr I's trilingual inscription at the Kaʿba-ye Zardošt, Naqš-e Rostam (mid-3rd c. CE), §3.17, lists **Mazūn** among empire territories. The Middle Persian *Šahrestānīhā ī Ērānšahr* (8th c.) §25 records Ardashir I appointing Ošag of Hagar as *marzbān* over "Dō-sar and Borg-gil by the wall of the Arabs"; Yāqūt's *Muʿjam al-Buldān* V:122 notes Ardashir deported the Azd from Oman to Šeḥr in Hadhramawt. *Kārnāmag ī Ardašīr ī Pābagān* mentions "Tāzīgān ud Mazūnīgān." Khosrow I (r. 531–579) appointed the Lakhmid al-Mundhir III to Mazūn c. 531/2 (Potts, "Arabia ii. The Sasanians and Arabia," *Encyclopaedia Iranica*, 2012).

**Critical counter-evidence**: Derek Kennet, "The decline of eastern Arabia in the Sasanian period," *AAE* 18 (2007): 86–122 — re-survey of pottery and sites concludes late Sasanian eastern Arabia was "an impoverished region with a low population that was not closely integrated into the Sasanian economy." Munt, "Oman and Late Sasanian Imperialism," *AAE* 2017: 264–284 — direct Sasanian admin was real but Wilkinson's earlier picture of intense agricultural development is unsupported by survey. The classic synthesis remains J. C. Wilkinson, "The Julanda of Oman," *Journal of Oman Studies* 1 (1975): 97–108 and *Water and Tribal Settlement in South-East Arabia* (Clarendon, 1977: 133–155).

**Fire temples and Zoroastrian survival.** **No archaeologically confirmed Zoroastrian fire temple has been excavated in Oman.** No Zoroastrian funerary tower (*dakhma*); no Pahlavi stone inscriptions in Oman known to publication. Rustāq's *Qalʿat al-Kisra* and Nakhal Fort are popularly called pre-Islamic but the standing structures are 17th-c. or later; the "Persian influence" tourism literature is not archaeologically substantiated as Sasanian cult.

**Julanda as Sasanian vassal.** The Azd Shanūʾa clan was elevated by Persians to manage the Arab tribal interior (Wilkinson 1975, JOS 1). The dual-rule treaty — coastal Persians + interior Julandā collecting tithe at Dibba — is reported in al-Awtabī's *Ansāb* and later in al-Sālimī's *Tuḥfat al-Aʿyān*. **Confidence: H** on administrative presence; **M** on intensity; **H** on the null for fire-temples; **H** on Julandā as Persian vassal.

### (d) Mesopotamian transmission via the copper trade

Sargonic and Ur III tablets (c. 2350–2000 BCE) cite Magan as Mesopotamia's principal copper source; Naram-Sin campaigned against Manium of Magan c. 2250 BCE. Potts (*The Arabian Gulf in Antiquity*, Oxford 1990) identified >150 copper-mining/smelting sites in Oman (Maysar, Wadi Jizzi, Wadi Samad). Material exchanges include Mesopotamian Jemdet-Nasr pottery in Hafit tombs, Sumerian-style cylinder seals in some Umm an-Nar contexts, Indus stamp seals at Ras al-Jinz, Harappan red-and-black pottery and carnelian at Bat, Hili, and Tell Abraq.

**Religious transmission specifically: very limited and indirect.** **No Sumerian or Akkadian deity name is attested in Oman**; no Mesopotamian-style ziggurat or temple; no cuneiform school. The Gudea diorite statuary in Mesopotamia reflects raw-material *export*, not religious export. Some scholars suggest the snake-cult parallels resonate with broader Near Eastern serpent symbolism (Mesopotamian Ningishzida, Elamite serpent imagery) but the SE Arabian snake cult is primarily autochthonous. **Confidence: VH** for copper-trade economic link; **L** for direct religious transmission.

### (e) Fate of pre-Islamic religion when Islam arrived

**The letter and conversion (629–630 CE).** Al-Balādhurī's *Futūḥ al-Buldān*: Muḥammad sent ʿAmr b. al-ʿĀṣ al-Sahmī (with Abū Zayd al-Anṣārī) bearing a letter to **Jayfar and ʿAbd, sons of al-Julandā**, then ruling jointly at Sohar. A leather manuscript claimed as the original 8/630 CE letter (with seal) is held at the National Museum of Oman; its authenticity is contested on paleographic grounds (the floral border has been read as later Persian-influenced ornamentation). The standard text begins «بسم الله الرحمن الرحيم، من محمد رسول الله إلى جيفر وعبد ابني الجلندى، سلام على من اتبع الهدى، أما بعد فإني أدعوكما بدعاية الإسلام، أسلما تسلما...». Al-Ṭabarī's *Tārīkh* and Ibn Saʿd's *Ṭabaqāt* record peaceful acceptance; al-Sālimī's *Tuḥfat al-Aʿyān bi-sīrat ahl ʿUmān* I:51ff (Cairo 1928/1931, ed. Ibrāhīm Aṭfayyish) reproduces the narrative.

**Persian military expulsion (630 CE).** The Azd, allied with the Julandā brothers, defeated the Sasanian governor (named Maskān/Maskūt in variant readings) at **Dastajird in Sohar** in 630 CE. The Persians fled, "leaving their silver and gold" (Wilkinson 1975, JOS 1). Wilkinson (cited in Munt 2017): "Ṣuḥār was the main Persian centre on the coast with a standing army based in the fortified quarter of Dastajird" — until Arab eviction at the conversion to Islam.

**The Ridda war and the Battle of Dibba (632–633 CE).** After Muḥammad's death, Laqīṭ b. Mālik al-Azdī (Dhū al-Tāj, "the Crowned One"), an apostate rival to the Julandā, rebelled. Abū Bakr sent Ḥudhayfa b. Miḥsan al-Ghalfānī and ʿArfaja al-Bāriqī, then ʿIkrima b. Abī Jahl from Yamāma as reinforcement; combined forces defeated Laqīṭ at Dibba; casualties of 10,000 are reported (al-Ṭabarī). The "Day of Dibba" is framed as the defeat of paganism by Islam — though in practice it was also the consolidation of Julandā loyalty under Medinan suzerainty.

**Fate of Persians and Zoroastrianism after 630 CE.** The Sasanian garrison was militarily expelled in 630; no source records mass conversion of the resident Persian population; they "evacuated the country." Pockets of Persian-descent population (Bayāsira, ʿAjam, later Lawātiyya, Baluchi) survived along the Bāṭinah coast and converted to Islam over generations. **No source records the destruction of an Omani fire temple by Muslims** — because no fire temples have been excavated. By the 7th c. CE the active cultic landscape included Christian (Nestorian: bishoprics at Mazūn/Sohar attested in Syriac synod lists 5th–7th c.), Jewish trader communities, Persian Zoroastrians (military), and tribal Arab paganism (limited evidence). **Indigenous pre-Islamic Omani religion** (the snake-cult horizon) **had ended c. 300 BCE–300 CE** — well before Islam — and was not "suppressed" by Muslims because it had already ceased.

**Analysis.** Islam's arrival in Oman was *simultaneously* a religious conversion of the ruling Julandā and an anti-Persian liberation movement. The "peaceful" narrative is real for the Julandā but masks the subsequent Ridda war and the military expulsion of Persians. Zoroastrianism's footprint in Oman appears to have been confined to the garrison community, which left in 630. **Pre-Islamic Omani religious knowledge was not preserved underground in Oman as a clandestine cult**; it had already died centuries before. What got preserved through the conversion was the *Julandā political system* and Arab tribal genealogy — which is exactly what al-Awtabī's *Ansāb* and al-Sālimī's *Tuḥfat al-Aʿyān* record. **Confidence: H** on Julandā conversion; **H** on Persian expulsion; **H** on the Battle of Dibba; **M** on letter manuscript authenticity; **H** on the null for fire-temple destruction.

