The Musnad in al-Wārijlānī's recension contains **1,005** reports across 4 parts. Parts I–II = **742 marfūʿ muttaṣil** (Mansouri/Drissi/Mizouri 2018 critical edn., Oman/Europe University). Some Ibadi sources cite 743 marfūʿ + 27 mawqūf/maqṭūʿ athar for the original core (Khamīs al-Shaqṣī, *Manhaj al-Ṭālibīn*). Al-Wārijlānī added Part III (140 athār — polemical) and Part IV (123 — Maḥbūb b. al-Ruḥayl ← al-Rabīʿ; Aflaḥ b. ʿAbd al-Wahhāb ← Abū Ghānim al-Khurāsānī; marāsīl Jābir). Bukhārī: ~2,602 unique. Muslim: ~3,033 unique. **Confidence: VH.**

### (a) Shared with Bukhārī/Muslim

**No published comprehensive concordance located.** This is a methodologically important finding in itself: the comparative literature exists but is *qualitative*. Muḥammad Idrīs's *Takhrīj aḥādīth al-Musnad wa-muqāranatuhā* tabulates *shawāhid* without an aggregate count. ʿAbd al-Raḥmān al-Sālik's dissertation *Musnad al-Rabīʿ b. Ḥabīb ʿinda al-Ibāḍiyya: Dirāsa Naqdiyya* and Saʿd b. ʿAbdallāh Āl Ḥumayd's *Aqsām al-ḥadīth fī Musnad al-Rabīʿ — Dirāsa Naqdiyya* (Kulliyyat Uṣūl al-Dīn, 2009) classify by sound/weak but do not publish a Bukhārī/Muslim overlap statistic. The only published quantitative comparison Āl Ḥumayd cites is Musnad ↔ *Jāmiʿ Ibn Baraka* (Ibadi): "thalāthat arbāʿ aḥādīth al-Musnad lā tūjad fī kitāb Ibn Baraka." Al-Sālimī's *Sharḥ al-Jāmiʿ al-Ṣaḥīḥ* asserts qualitatively that "most" of the 742 marfūʿ overlap with Sunni transmissions, sometimes with slight variant wording.

**Reasoned estimate (explicitly not published).** Shared-with-Bukhārī-or-Muslim plausibly falls in **~300–450 of 742 marfūʿ** (~40–60%); *muttafaq ʿalayh* (both) substantially lower, ~150–250. The Omani Sharīfīn essay (omandaily.om, 2021) calls for exactly such studies to be carried out — implying they have not been. **Confidence: L** for the numerical range; **H** for the claim that no published concordance exists.

### (b) Unique to the Musnad

Again no published count. Structural argument: Parts III + IV (140 + 123 = **263**) are essentially unique to the Ibadi tradition; from the 742 marfūʿ a residual ~150–300 plausibly lack Ṣaḥīḥayn parallels. Estimated total unique: ~**400–550 of 1,005**. **Confidence: L** numerical; **M** structural.

### (c) Unique tawḥīd / divine-attribute material

No published quantitative isolation of this category. Part III is the natural locus — the polemical section explicitly used against opponents on *qadar*, *ruʾyat Allāh*, *khalq al-Qurʾān*, *al-imāma*. Nada al-Qushayrī's 2018 article *Ruʾyat Allāh ʿinda al-Ibāḍiyya — Dirāsa Naqdiyya* (BFSA Journals) confirms that the Ibadi anti-ruʾya position relies on these specific Musnad proof-texts: «مستدلين بالأدلة الواردة في مسند الربيع بن حبيب الذي يعتبر عندهم المرجع المعتمد». Reasoned estimate: ~**40–80** of the 140 Part-III athār concern tawḥīd/ṣifāt/ruʾya/khalq al-Qurʾān/qadar. **Confidence: L** numerical; **H** structural.

### (d) Variant matn with theological consequence

No comprehensive matn-divergence catalog located. Specific cases assembled from primary sources:

**The opening hadith.** Musnad #1 (al-Wārijlānī's arrangement, Part I): «نية المؤمن خير من عمله، ونية الفاجر شر من عمله» — *"The intention of the believer is better than his deed; and the intention of the corrupt one is worse than his deed."* Sunni opener: Bukhārī #1 / Muslim #1907 «إنما الأعمال بالنيات» via the ʿUmar narration. The Ibadi version (i) drops the ʿUmar route, (ii) adds the moralized *fājir*-clause, (iii) routes through Ibn ʿAbbās ← Jābir ← Abū ʿUbayda. Al-Albānī (*Silsila Ḍaʿīfa* #2789) declares the second clause lacks any independent authentic chain; the closest parallel is a weak Ṭabarānī mawqūf via Sahl b. Saʿd (*al-Muʿjam al-Kabīr* #5942). **Theological implication**: the Ibadi version foregrounds intention over external act — coherent with the stricter Ibadi *takfīr-of-murtakib-al-kabīra* position.

**Anti-anthropomorphism cluster.** The Musnad's recension of the *raʾā rabbahu* / *kursī* / *yad Allāh* material lacks the anthropomorphic-leaning Ṣaḥīḥayn forms: Bukhārī #554 («إنكم سترون ربكم كما ترون القمر»), #7437 (*ḥadīth al-shafāʿa* with «حتى يضع الجبار قدمه»), #7416 (*ḥadīth al-aṭīṭ*), #7406 («ينزل ربنا»), Muslim #181 (*ḍaḥik Allāh*). Multiple Ibadi and academic sources note the Musnad's tanzīh-compliant orientation as a feature. **Confidence: M** — pending verification by full concordance search.

**Ḥadīth al-shafāʿa.** The Musnad version «ثم يقال لي يا محمد اشفع نشفعك» appears without the Sunni anthropomorphic clause «يضع الجبار قدمه على النار» (Bukhārī #7449, #4848). Ibadi commentary rejects *shafāʿa li-ahl al-kabāʾir* — a structural Ibadi disagreement with Sunnism.

**Musnad #844.** Al-Albānī notes a mawqūf-on-Abū-Hurayra of material that is *marfūʿ* in al-Bukhārī — the Ibadi version downgrades a Prophetic statement to a Companion statement, removing binding authority. The isnād runs through Bishr al-Marīsī (the Muʿtazilite, d. 218 AH), Muḥammad b. Yaʿlā (Jahmī, *matrūk*), al-Ḥasan b. Dīnār (*kadhdhāb*), Khaṣīb b. Jaḥdar (*kadhdhāb*) — an anachronism noted by al-Albānī: "هذا أولًا سند ليس له علاقة بالربيع، فمن الذي أدخله في هذا الكتاب؟"

**Pattern.** Where Musnad and Ṣaḥīḥayn share a base hadith, the Ibadi version tends to (i) drop anthropomorphic clauses, (ii) reframe marfūʿ → mawqūf where the marfūʿ form has rejected theological implications (shafāʿa, ruʾya), (iii) add Ibadi-distinctive parallelisms (the *fājir* clause). Directionality strongly supports the project's "anti-anthropomorphism as diagnostic" frame — but a Sunni reader interprets the same pattern as Ibadi tampering, while an Ibadi reader interprets it as Sunni anthropomorphic accretion. **The textual evidence underdetermines the directionality.** **Confidence: M** pattern; **L** specific examples.

### (e) Al-Albānī's specific critiques and the Ibadi defense

**Al-Albānī's named work**: *Silsilat al-Aḥādīth al-Ḍaʿīfa wa-l-Mawḍūʿa wa-atharuhā al-sayyiʾ fī al-umma*, Dār al-Maʿārif, Riyadh, 1st ed. 1412/1992, 14 vols.

| Silsila # | Matn | Musnad location | Al-Albānī's basis |
|---|---|---|---|
| #2789 (6/304) | «نية المؤمن خير من عمله، ونية الفاجر شر من عمله» | Musnad #1 | al-Rabīʿ "إباضي مجهول ليس له ذكر في كتب أئمتنا"; Abū ʿUbayda *majhūl*; the *fājir* clause has no corroborating chain. |
| #9562 | «إذا خُطب إليكم كفؤ فلا تردّوه فنعوذ بالله من بوار البنات» | Musnad #513 (Bāb al-nikāḥ) | Mawḍūʿ. "الربيع هذا نكرة لا يعرف… حتى الإباضيون لم يستطيعوا أن يذكروا لنا شيئًا من تاريخ حياته." |
| (ref. 1384/1429) | «ألا إن رحى الإسلام دائرة، اعرضوا حديثي على الكتاب…» | Bāb al-ʿilm | *Ḍaʿīf jiddan*; Yazīd b. Rabīʿa *matrūk* per Nasāʾī, Dāraquṭnī; Bukhārī: "aḥādīthuhū munkara". |
