Al-Albānī's summary verdict (*Silsila* 6/304; verbatim from islamqa.info, dd-sunnah.net): «والربيع بن حبيب — وهو الفراهيدي البصري — إباضي مجهول، ليس له ذكر في كتب أئمتنا، ومسنده هذا هو "صحيح الإباضية"! وهو مليء بالأحاديث الواهية والمنكرة.» In *Ṣifat Ṣalāt al-Nabī* p. 188 he writes: «رواه ربيعُهم في مسنده المجهول». Reaffirmed by Mashhūr Ḥasan, *Kutub ḥadhdhara minhā al-ʿulamāʾ* 2/295–296. **Confidence: VH** on Silsila numbers and verbatim verdicts.

**The Ibadi defense.** The canonical work is **Saʿīd b. Mabrūk al-Qannūbī**, *al-Imām al-Rabīʿ b. Ḥabīb — makānatuhū wa-musnaduhū* (multiple printings; alsaidia.com): defends al-Rabīʿ's biography, sets birth ~75–80 AH and death ~150–200 AH, defends Abū ʿUbayda, and rebuts al-Albānī's specific charges. Al-Qannūbī also authored ***al-Sayf al-Ḥādd fī al-Radd ʿalā man akhadha bi-ḥadīth al-āḥād fī masāʾil al-iʿtiqād*** (islamarchive.cc/bibliography-ar/2047483) — a methodological work rejecting *āḥād* hadith as proof in ʿaqīda, not specifically anti-Albānī. **Important clarification: the title cited in the research brief ("al-Sayf al-Ḥadīd fī al-Radd ʿalā al-Albānī fī tadʿīfihi al-Rabīʿ b. Ḥabīb") does not match any located work; it appears to conflate al-Qannūbī's two works.** The Mufti Aḥmad b. Ḥamad al-Khalīlī publicly endorses Qannūbī as the principal Ibadi muḥaddith on this question. **Confidence: H** on the bibliographic clarification.

**The rijāl question — Ibn Ḥibbān and the "two Rabīʿs."** Ibn Ḥibbān's *al-Thiqāt* lists two distinct Rabīʿ b. Ḥabībs: (i) a Basran who narrates from al-Ḥasan and Ibn Sīrīn, and (ii) Abū Salama al-Ḥanafī of Yamāma. Yaḥyā b. Maʿīn (per al-Dūrī's *Tārīkh* 3/353): «الربيع بن حبيب أيضًا صرى، يروي عن الحسن وابن سيرين وهو ثقة.» Neither is the Ibadi **al-Rabīʿ b. Ḥabīb al-Farāhīdī al-Azdī**, who belongs to a later *ṭabaqa* and reaches al-Ḥasan or Ibn Sīrīn only through two intermediaries (not directly), as visible from the Musnad's own isnāds (#475, #713, #848, #852). The Ibadi case (per Wikipedia AR, alsaidia.com) conflates these. Ibn ʿAdī's *al-Kāmil* 3/137 records of "al-Rabīʿ al-Ghaṭafānī": «وأنا لا أعرفه ولا أدري من يروي عنه وعن من يروي عنه، ولم ينسبه ربيع بن من، فهو مجهول من كل جهاته» — and some Ibadi sources do nisbah al-Farāhīdī to Ghuḍfān/Ghaṭafān, suggesting this is plausibly the same person Ibn Maʿīn (in this entry) found *majhūl*. **Confidence: VH** on the two-Rabīʿ distinction; **H** that the Ibn Ḥibbān *Thiqāt* entries Ibadis invoke are for a different person.

**Cross-reference to project hypothesis.** The Musnad is a productive test case precisely because (1) it claims an isnād parallel to a Basran Sunni-acknowledged tābiʿī (Jābir b. Zayd), (2) it systematically lacks the most theologically loaded anthropomorphic matns of the Ṣaḥīḥayn, and (3) the historical evidentiary chain for it as a genuine 2nd-c. text is weak — first MS attestations are post-Wārijlānī (6th/12th c.). Either the Ṣaḥīḥayn contain post-Rabīʿ anthropomorphic accretions, or the Musnad's tanzīh-compliance reflects post-2nd-c. Ibadi editing. **The data underdetermine the directionality.** A cleaner test would identify Ibadi hadiths with strong pre-Wārijlānī attestation — *Mudawwanat Abī Ghānim al-Khurāsānī* (late 2nd c. AH) is the most promising candidate for that follow-up.

---

## Conclusion: how the picture shifts after these six inquiries

Three findings change the project's working model.

**First, the diagnostic does not generalize.** The Ibadi case demonstrates that maximal anti-anthropomorphism for God can coexist with maximal literalism about jinn — because *tanzīh* is principled creator-doctrine governed by *mukhālafa li-l-ḥawādith*, not a generalized demythologizing impulse. **Anti-anthropomorphism is not a reliable proxy for naturalistic cosmology.** The project should expect the same asymmetry in Muʿtazilī and Imāmī traditions: literal jinn, transcendent God.

**Second, the "species hardware limitation" reading of Iblīs is textually grounded in mainstream Ibadi tafsīr.** Aṭfayyish on Q 17:64 («وجند إبليس يومئذ من الجن») together with the Ibadi consensus on Q 18:50, Q 7:12, and the *istithnāʾ munqaṭiʿ* reading of Q 2:34 give the project its strongest documentary warrant for the frame so far: Iblīs's *fisq* flows from his jinn-substance — that fire-substance is the precondition of *ikhtiyār* (which angels of *nūr* lack), and *ikhtiyār* is the precondition of disobedience.

**Third, the textual-suppression signal is most concrete in the Naffāth burning.** The Diwan of Jābir was destroyed not by Umayyad authorities but by a doctrinally aligned insider (Naffāth b. Naṣr al-Nafūsī), opposed to the Rustamid Ibadi mainstream. The surviving Jābir corpus is conspicuously empty of cosmology, rūḥ, and jinn material — the categories that would normally have appeared in a fully transmitted *ʿaqīda*-inclusive Diwan. This is exactly the *asymmetric loss* the project's hypothesis predicts.

Two cautions temper these gains. The Musnad-as-2nd-century-document case is contested; the earliest secure manuscript attestation is post-al-Wārijlānī (6th/12th c.), and no published quantitative concordance with the Ṣaḥīḥayn exists — meaning the directionality of the divergence (Ibadi preservation of original tanzīh vs. Ibadi editorial selection) cannot be settled from textual evidence alone. And on Magan, religious knowledge is mute — there is a coherent autochthonous Iron-Age serpent cult tied to copper and water, but **no deity is known by name from any site in Oman**. The "what was lost when Islam arrived" question collapses for Oman specifically because indigenous pre-Islamic religion had already died centuries before Islam: what arrived in 630 CE met Christians, Jews, a Persian military garrison, and a moribund tribal paganism — not a living indigenous cult to suppress.

The most productive next moves are concrete: (i) direct browser retrieval of Aṭfayyish on Q 2:30–39, Q 7:11–13, Q 15:26–43, Q 18:50, Q 38:71–85 from altafsir.com / greattafsirs.com (bot-blocked in this session); (ii) systematic concordance of Musnad ↔ Ṣaḥīḥayn (does not exist in the published literature); (iii) inspection of *Mudawwanat Abī Ghānim al-Khurāsānī* as a pre-Wārijlānī Ibadi witness; (iv) targeted search of Bayān al-Sharʿ for Jābir-attributed cosmological material at exact volume/page resolution.
